{"title_page": "Marion Hutton", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image            = Marion Hutton.jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| caption          = Marion Hutton in 1944\n| birth_name       = Marion Thornburg\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1919|3|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]], U.S. \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1987|1|10|1919|3|10}}\n| death_place      = [[Kirkland, Washington]], U.S. \n| occupation       = [[Singing|Singer]] and actress\n| spouse           = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Jack Philbin|1940|1949|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Jack Douglas|1949|1954|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Vic Schoen]]<br>|1954}}\n}}\n| children         = 3\n| relatives          = [[Betty Hutton]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Marion Hutton''' (born '''Marion Thornburg'''; March 10, 1919 &ndash; January 10, 1987) was an American [[singing|singer]] and [[actress]]. She is best remembered for her singing with the [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]] from 1938\u20131942. She was the sister of actress and singer [[Betty Hutton]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn as Marion Thornburg in [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]], she was the elder sister of actress [[Betty Hutton]]. They were raised in [[Battle Creek, Michigan]]. The sisters' father abandoned the family when they were both young; he later committed [[suicide]]. Their mother worked a variety of jobs to support the family until she became a successful [[Rum-running|bootlegger]].<ref>[http://www.slipcue.com/music/jazz/artists/hutton.html Marion Hutton biodata], slipcue.com; accessed September 26, 2015.</ref> Both sisters sang with the [[Vincent Lopez|Vincent Lopez Orchestra]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bettyhutton-440091.html Betty Hutton obituary], independent.co.uk; accessed September 26, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Discovery by Glenn Miller==\nHutton was discovered by [[Glenn Miller]] and was invited to join the [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]] in 1938.<!-- This sentence was deleted because it was an opinion and wasn't objective -->  \"I was only seventeen then [...] and so Glenn and Helen [Miller] became my legal guardians. He was like a father because I never had a father I remembered.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Glenn Miller and His Orchestra|last=Simon|first=George T.|authorlink=George T. Simon|year=1980|publisher=DaCapo|location=New York|ISBN =0-306-80129-9\n|page=139|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DvLC5_RJS0MC}}</ref> Miller wanted Hutton to appear as an all-American girl, so on her first few performances, he introduced her as \"Sissy Jones.\" The pseudonym was not used beyond those first performances.<ref>Simon, pp.138-139</ref>\n\nHutton was not allowed to sing in the nightclubs due to the fact she was underage. Miller and his wife Helen signed papers to officially declare themselves foster parents to serve as Hutton's chaperone in the nightclubs which allowed her access in these venues. Marion Hutton considered herself more an entertainer than a singer.<ref>Simon, p. 139</ref> Hutton remained an important part of the Miller band.<ref>Simon, pp. 260-61</ref> She remained with Miller on and off, until the orchestra disbanded in 1942.\n\n==Film career==\n[[File:Marion Hutton et al.jpg|thumb|left|Hutton with [[Mel Torme]] and [[Gordon MacRae]] in 1947.]]\n[[Jeanine Basinger]], a film historian and professor at [[Wesleyan University]] in [[Middletown, Connecticut]], refers to Hutton in her chapter on Marion's younger sister, actress and singer [[Betty Hutton]] in the 2007 book ''The Star Machine''. Basinger asserts that in the early forties, Marion was more popular than her sister Betty.<ref>This book is a study of the studio system in Hollywood.</ref> Marion Hutton had a small role in the film ''[[Orchestra Wives]]'' (1942; Twentieth Century Fox), in which the Glenn Miller Orchestra starred. After Miller joined the [[United States Army|Army]] in 1942, she went with fellow Miller performers [[Tex Beneke]] and the [[Modernaires]] on a theater tour.<ref>Simon, p. 314</ref>\n\nThe next important event in her entertainment career was a role in ''[[In Society]]'' with [[Abbott and Costello]] in 1944.  Marion Hutton appeared with the [[Desi Arnaz]] orchestra in October 1947 at the Radio City Theatre in [[Minneapolis]].<ref>[http://www.parabrisas.com/d_huttonm.php \"Solid: Marion Hutton\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218151241/http://www.parabrisas.com/d_huttonm.php |date=2009-02-18 }}</ref> As the 1940s wound down, so did Marion's career.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Star Machine|last=Basinger|first=Jeanine|authorlink=Jeanine Basinger|year=2007|publisher=Knopf|isbn=1-4000-4130-9|page=493|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=idRkAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> Her last film role was in 1949, acting in the [[Marx Brothers]]' ''[[Love Happy]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nHutton was married three times. She married publicist and television producer Jack Philbin in 1940. She and Philbin had two sons, John and Phillip. Her next marriage, to writer [[Jack Douglas (writer)|Jack Douglas]], produced a third son, Peter. Peter Hemming is a noted photojournalist. Her last and longest marriage was in 1954 to [[Vic Schoen]], an arranger for the [[Andrews Sisters]] and [[Bing Crosby]], among other artists in the 1940s. The couple remained married until her death in 1987.<ref>[http://www.parabrisas.com/d_schoenv.php \"Solid: Vic Schoen\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212204239/http://www.parabrisas.com/d_schoenv.php |date=2008-12-12 }}</ref> Looking back on her first marriage, in 1974 she told George T. Simon, \"[W]hat I wanted most of all was to be a wife and mother. I had no drive for a career.\"<ref>Simon, p. 224</ref>\n\nIn 1965 according to the ''New York Times'', Marion Hutton sought treatment for various addictions. Hutton went back to school in her late fifties. She received two psychology degrees and found work at a local hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hWwaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7ykEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7028,7287904&dq=perry+como&hl=en|title=Whatever became of: Marion Hutton|date=May 31, 1983|publisher=The Milwaukee Journal|accessdate=December 2, 2010}}</ref> During the 1960s and 70s, Hutton and Schoen lived in [[Laguna Beach]] but later moved due to increasing financial problems.<ref>{{cite book|last=Simon|first=George Thomas|title=Glenn Miller and His Orchestra|date=August 22, 1980|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0306801297|page=137}}</ref> In 1981, Hutton and Schoen moved from [[Irvine, California]] to [[Kirkland, Washington]], and founded [http://www.residencexii.org Residence XII], a drug addiction center to help alcoholics and addicts. She was the executive director.\n\nSchoen and Hutton performed many fund raisers for this addiction center. Hutton and [[Vic Schoen|Schoen]] had both struggled with [[alcoholism]] and in the 1970s both were finally able to quit drinking and joined [[Alcoholics Anonymous|AA]]. They attended meetings regularly until the late 1980s and helped many struggling alcoholics by recounting their anecdotes and life lessons they had learned throughout the years. [[Vic Schoen|Schoen]] arranged music for '' [[Glenn Miller]] Remembered, '' a [[PBS]] production video taped in [[Seattle]], 1984, starring [[Tex Beneke]] and Marion Hutton.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\n==Death==\nMarion Hutton died of [[cancer]] on January 10, 1987 at age 67, in [[Kirkland, Washington]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DEFDA1338F931A25752C0A961948260 Obituary], ''The New York Times''; accessed September 26, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Selected Discography==\n*1939 \"Ding Dong the Witch is Dead\", with Glenn Miller and his Orchestra, Bluebird (recorded July 12, 1939)\n*1942 \"That's Sabotage\" with Glenn Miller and his Orchestra, Victor (recorded June 17, 1942)\n*1940 \"The Rhumba Jumps\" vocal with Tex Beneke, with Glenn Miller and his Orchestra, Bluebird (recorded January 26, 1940)\n*1940 \"Say 'Si Si'\" with Glenn Miller and his Orchestra, Bluebird 10622 (recorded January 26, 1940)\n*1942.\"(I Got a Gal in) Kalamazoo\" vocal with Tex Beneke and the Modernaires, with Glenn Miller and his Orchestra,Victor 27934-A\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|404649}}\n*{{Find a Grave|7691375}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hutton, Marion}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Michigan]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Big band singers]]\n[[Category:People from Battle Creek, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kirkland, Washington]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Glenn Miller Orchestra members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image            = Marion Hutton.jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| caption          = Marion Hutton in 1944\n| birth_name       = Marion Thornburg\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1919|3|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]], U.S. \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1987|1|10|1919|3|10}}\n| death_place      = [[Kirkland, Washington]], U.S. \n| occupation       = [[Singing|Singer]] and actress\n| spouse           = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Jack Philbin|1940|1949|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Jack Douglas|1949|1954|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Vic Schoen]]<br>|1954}}\n}}\n| children         = 3\n| relatives          = [[Betty Hutton]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Marion Hutton''' (born '''Marion Thornburg'''; March 10, 1919 &ndash; January 10, 1987) was an American [[singing|singer]] and [[actress]]. She is best remembered for her singing with the [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]] from 1938\u20131942. She was the sister of actress and singer [[Betty Hutton]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn as Marion Thornburg in [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]], she was the elder sister of actress [[Betty Hutton]]. They were raised in [[Battle Creek, Michigan]]. The sisters' father abandoned the family when they were both young; he later committed [[suicide]]. Their mother worked a variety of jobs to support the family until she became a successful [[Rum-running|bootlegger]].<ref>[http://www.slipcue.com/music/jazz/artists/hutton.html Marion Hutton biodata], slipcue.com; accessed September 26, 2015.</ref> Both sisters sang with the [[Vincent Lopez|Vincent Lopez Orchestra]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bettyhutton-440091.html Betty Hutton obituary], independent.co.uk; accessed September 26, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Discovery by Glenn Miller==\nHutton was discovered by [[Glenn Miller]] and was invited to join the [[Glenn Miller Orchestra]] in 1938.<!-- This sentence was deleted because it was an opinion and wasn't objective -->  \"I was only seventeen then [...] and so Glenn and Helen [Miller] became my legal guardians. He was like a father because I never had a father I remembered.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Glenn Miller and His Orchestra|last=Simon|first=George T.|authorlink=George T. Simon|year=1980|publisher=DaCapo|location=New York|ISBN =0-306-80129-9\n|page=139|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DvLC5_RJS0MC}}</ref> Miller wanted Hutton to appear as an all-American girl, so on her first few performances, he introduced her as \"Sissy Jones.\" The pseudonym was not used beyond those first performances.<ref>Simon, pp.138-139</ref>\n\nHutton was not allowed to sing in the nightclubs due to the fact she was underage. Miller and his wife Helen signed papers to officially declare themselves foster parents to serve as Hutton's chaperone in the nightclubs which allowed her access in these venues. Marion Hutton considered herself more an entertainer than a singer.<ref>Simon, p. 139</ref> Hutton remained an important part of the Miller band.<ref>Simon, pp. 260-61</ref> She remained with Miller on and off, until the orchestra disbanded in 1942.\n\n==Film career==\n[[File:Marion Hutton et al.jpg|thumb|left|Hutton with [[Mel Torme]] and [[Gordon MacRae]] in 1947.]]\n[[Jeanine Basinger]], a film historian and professor at [[Wesleyan University]] in [[Middletown, Connecticut]], refers to Hutton in her chapter on Marion's younger sister, actress and singer [[Betty Hutton]] in the 2007 book ''The Star Machine''. Basinger asserts that in the early forties, Marion was more popular than her sister Betty.<ref>This book is a study of the studio system in Hollywood.</ref> Marion Hutton had a small role in the film ''[[Orchestra Wives]]'' (1942; Twentieth Century Fox), in which the Glenn Miller Orchestra starred. After Miller joined the [[United States Army|Army]] in 1942, she went with fellow Miller performers [[Tex Beneke]] and the [[Modernaires]] on a theater tour.<ref>Simon, p. 314</ref>\n\nThe next important event in her entertainment career was a role in ''[[In Society]]'' with [[Abbott and Costello]] in 1944.  Marion Hutton appeared with the [[Desi Arnaz]] orchestra in October 1947 at the Radio City Theatre in [[Minneapolis]].<ref>[http://www.parabrisas.com/d_huttonm.php \"Solid: Marion Hutton\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218151241/http://www.parabrisas.com/d_huttonm.php |date=2009-02-18 }}</ref> As the 1940s wound down, so did Marion's career.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Star Machine|last=Basinger|first=Jeanine|authorlink=Jeanine Basinger|year=2007|publisher=Knopf|isbn=1-4000-4130-9|page=493|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=idRkAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> Her last film role was in 1949, acting in the [[Marx Brothers]]' ''[[Love Happy]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nHutton was married three times. She married publicist and television producer Jack Philbin in 1940. She and Philbin had two sons, John and Phillip. Her next marriage, to writer [[Jack Douglas (writer)|Jack Douglas]], produced a third son, Peter. Peter Hemming is a noted photojournalist. Her last and longest marriage was in 1954 to [[Vic Schoen]], an arranger