ponica]]\n| blank2_name_sec1        = - Flower\n| blank2_info_sec1        = [[Camellia japonica]]\n| blank3_name_sec1        = - Bird\n| blank3_info_sec1        = \n| blank4_name_sec1        =\n| blank4_info_sec1        =\n| blank5_name_sec1        =\n| blank5_info_sec1        =\n| blank6_name_sec1        =\n| blank6_info_sec1        =\n| blank7_name_sec1        =\n| blank7_info_sec1        =\n<!-- blank fields (section 2) -->\n| blank_name_sec2         = Phone&nbsp;number\n| blank_info_sec2         =04992-2-1443\n| blank1_name_sec2        = Address\n| blank1_info_sec2        = 1-1-14 Motomachi, \u014cshima-machi, Tokyo 100-0101\n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = {{URL|http://www.town.oshima.tokyo.jp/}}\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''\u014cshima'''|\u5927\u5cf6\u753a| \u014cshima-machi}} is a [[List of towns in Japan|town]] located in [[\u014cshima Subprefecture (Tokyo)|\u014cshima Subprefecture]], [[Tokyo|Tokyo Metropolis]], [[Japan]]. {{As of|2016|02|01}}, the town had an estimated [[population]] of 7,762, and a [[population density]] of 85.5 persons per km\u00b2. Its total area is {{convert|90.76|sqkm|sqmi}}.\n\n==Geography==\n\u014cshima Town covers the island of [[Izu \u014cshima]], in the [[Izu Islands|Izu archipelago]] in the [[Philippine Sea]], {{convert|120|km|mi}} south of central Tokyo.\n\n== Climate ==\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location     = Oshima, Tokyo\n| metric first = yes\n| single line  = yes\n| Jan high C = 10.7\n| Feb high C = 11.2\n| Mar high C = 13.5\n| Apr high C = 18.0\n| May high C = 21.5\n| Jun high C = 24.0\n| Jul high C = 27.1\n| Aug high C = 29.2\n| Sep high C = 26.2\n| Oct high C = 21.5\n| Nov high C = 17.4\n| Dec high C = 13.3\n| year high C = 19.5\n|Jan mean C = 7.3\n|Feb mean C = 7.4\n|Mar mean C = 9.9\n|Apr mean C = 14.2\n|May mean C = 17.9\n|Jun mean C = 20.8\n|Jul mean C = 24.1\n|Aug mean C = 25.7\n|Sep mean C = 23.0\n|Oct mean C = 18.5\n|Nov mean C = 14.2\n|Dec mean C = 9.9\n|year mean C = 16.1\n| Jan low C = 3.7\n| Feb low C = 3.4\n| Mar low C = 6.2\n| Apr low C = 10.3\n| May low C = 14.5\n| Jun low C = 18.1\n| Jul low C = 21.8\n| Aug low C = 23.1\n| Sep low C = 20.5\n| Oct low C = 15.7\n| Nov low C = 11.0\n| Dec low C = 6.2\n| year low C = 12.9\n| rain colour = green\n| Jan rain mm = 130.5\n| Feb rain mm = 146.9\n| Mar rain mm = 258.2\n| Apr rain mm = 238.7\n| May rain mm = 259.8\n| Jun rain mm = 337.8\n| Jul rain mm = 246.5\n| Aug rain mm = 231.0\n| Sep rain mm = 353.1\n| Oct rain mm = 329.0\n| Nov rain mm = 194.9\n| Dec rain mm = 100.8\n| year rain mm = 2827.1\n| Jan rain days = 17.4\n| Feb rain days = 16.3\n| Mar rain days = 21.1\n| Apr rain days = 18.3\n| May rain days = 18.3\n| Jun rain days = 20.8\n| Jul rain days = 20.7\n| Aug rain days = 17.3\n| Sep rain days = 20.7\n| Oct rain days = 19.7\n| Nov rain days = 15.9\n| Dec rain days = 14.6\n| Jan humidity = 64\n| Feb humidity = 65\n| Mar humidity = 69\n| Apr humidity = 75\n| May humidity = 79\n| Jun humidity = 84\n| Jul humidity = 87\n| Aug humidity = 86\n| Sep humidity = 83\n| Oct humidity = 77\n| Nov humidity = 73\n| Dec humidity = 67\n| year humidity = 76\n| Jan sun = 151.7\n| Feb sun = 142.8\n| Mar sun = 148.6\n| Apr sun = 168.5\n| May sun = 171.6\n| Jun sun = 127.3\n| Jul sun = 142.6\n| Aug sun = 190.6\n| Sep sun = 135.9\n| Oct sun = 137.2\n| Nov sun = 138.7\n| Dec sun = 149.3\n| year sun = 1804.9\n|source 1                = <ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.data.jma.go.jp/obd/stats/etrn/view/nml_sfc_ym.php?prec_no=44&block_no=47675&year=&month=&day=&view=p1 |script-title=ja:\u904e\u53bb\u306e\u6c17\u8c61\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u691c\u7d22: \u5e73\u5e74\u5024\uff08\u5e74\u30fb\u6708\u3054\u3068\u306e\u5024\uff09 (\"Historical Climate data for Oshima\") | publisher = [[Japan Meteorological Agency]]}}</ref>\n| date     = April 2020\n}}\n\n==History==\nIt is uncertain when human settlement first began on \u014cshima, but archaeological finds from the [[J\u014dmon period]] have been discovered, and the island is mention from early [[Nara period]] documents. It is mentioned in historical records for its many volcanic eruptions. After the start of the [[Meiji period]], in 1878, the island came under the control of [[Tokyo-fu]] and was organized into six villages (Okada, Motomura, Senzu, Nomashi, Sashikiji and Habuminato) under Oshima subprefecture on April 1, 1908. The six villages were merged to form \u014cshima Town on April 1,1955.\n\nIn the mid-1930s, Izu \u014cshima became a popular suicide destination after three schoolgirls jumped into the active volcano in the center of the island. In 1935 alone, more than 800 suicides were recorded.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 10, 1936 |title=Japan's Fiery Pit of Death |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1936/05/10/page/98/article/japans-fiery-pit-of-death |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |access-date=June 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe central volcano on the island, [[Mount Mihara]] erupted in 1965 and again in 1986, forcing the temporary evacuation of the inhabitants.\n\nOn 16 October 2013, [[Typhoon Wipha (2013)|Typhoon Wipha]] passed over the island, dropping {{convert|80|cm|0|abbr=on}} of rain in 24 hours and causing a landslide that killed 35 people.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kyodo|first=Jiji|title=Izu-Oshima Island holds memorial for mudslide victims of Typhoon Wipha|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/11/16/national/izu-oshima-island-holds-memorial-for-mudslide-victims-of-typhoon-wipha/#.UqQfHMQW3l4|publisher=The Japan Times|accessdate=8 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\nFishing and seasonal tourism are the mainstays of the economy of \u014cshima.\n\n==Transportation==\n===Airport===\n*[[\u014cshima Airport]]\n\n==Education==\n\u014cshima town operates three public elementary schools and three public middle schools. The [[Tokyo Metropolitan Board of Education]] operated two high schools. \u014cshima High School is an agriculture school known for producing baseball players, and \u014cshima International Maritime Academy is a marine biology school. \u014cshima High School is attended primarily by children native to the island. \u014cshima International Maritime Academy draws students from mainland Tokyo and neighboring Izu in order to participate in its marine biology program.\n\n==Sister city relations==\n{{flagicon|USA}} - [[Hilo, Hawaii]], United States\n\n==Local attractions==\nThe island is known for its Camellia Festival, Hanabi Festival, five black sand beaches, and several [[onsen]]. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Oshima, Tokyo}}\n{{Portal|Tokyo}}\n*[http://www.town.oshima.tokyo.jp/ \u014cshima Town Official Website] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Tokyo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oshima, Tokyo}}\n[[Category:Towns in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = \u014cshima\n| native_name             ={{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|ja|\u5927\u5cf6\u753a}}}}}} \n| native_name_lang        = ja\n| settlement_type         = Town\n<!-- images, nickname, motto -->\n| image_skyline           =Oshima town office.JPG\n| imagesize               =\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           = \u014cshima Town Hall\n| image_flag              = Flag of Oshima, Tokyo.svg\n| flag_alt                =\n| image_seal              =Emblem of Oshima, Tokyo.svg\n| seal_alt                =\n| image_shield            =\n| shield_alt              =\n| image_blank_emblem      =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n<!-- maps and coordinates -->\n| image_map               = Oshima Town in Tokyo Prefecture Ja.svg\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             = Location of \u014cshima in [[Tokyo|Tokyo Metropolis]]\n| pushpin_map             = Japan\n| pushpin_label_position  = <!-- position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_map_alt        